Bootstrap: docker
From: nvidia/cuda:12.2.2-cudnn8-runtime-ubuntu22.04

%files
    ./borzoi_API_script_and_utils /src/borzoi_API_script_and_utils
    ./script_and_utils /src/script_and_utils
    ./borzoi_gpu_environment.yml /borzoi_gpu_environment.yml

%environment
    # Prevent automatic binding of host directories
    export APPTAINER_NO_MOUNT="home,tmp,proc,sys,dev"
    export PATH="/opt/conda/envs/borzoi-gpu/bin:$PATH"
    export LD_LIBRARY_PATH="/opt/conda/envs/borzoi-gpu/lib:/usr/local/cuda/lib64:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH"
    export CUDA_HOME="/opt/conda/envs/borzoi-gpu"
    export TF_CUDNN_USE_FRONTEND=1

%post
    # Install system packages needed for conda and building extensions
    echo "Installing system dependencies..."
    apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \
        wget \
        build-essential \
        zlib1g-dev
    apt-get clean && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

    # Install Miniconda
    echo "Setting up Miniconda..."
    wget --quiet https://repo.anaconda.com/miniconda/Miniconda3-latest-Linux-x86_64.sh -O /miniconda.sh
    bash /miniconda.sh -b -p /opt/conda
    rm /miniconda.sh

    # Temporarily add conda to PATH for this script
    export PATH=/opt/conda/bin:$PATH

    echo "Setting solver to classic and disabling plugins..."
    CONDA_NO_PLUGINS=true conda config --set solver classic

    # Create the conda environment using the correct file path
    echo "Creating Conda environment 'borzoi_gpu_environment'..."
    CONDA_NO_PLUGINS=true conda env create -f /borzoi_gpu_environment.yml
    conda clean -a -y

    # Activate the environment for subsequent commands
    echo "Activating Conda environment..."
    . /opt/conda/etc/profile.d/conda.sh
    conda activate borzoi-gpu

    echo "Installing Baskerville and Borzoi from local directories..."
    export SETUPTOOLS_SCM_PRETEND_VERSION="0.1"
    pip install --no-cache-dir \
        /src/borzoi_API_script_and_utils/baskerville \
        /src/borzoi_API_script_and_utils/borzoi
    
    echo "Installing flask..."
    pip install flask
    # pip install waitress

    # Set permissions to access all directories
    echo "Setting permissions..."
    chmod -R 755 /src

%runscript
    # This section defines the default run behavior of the container
    echo "Container is running with Borzoi GPU environment activated"
    export PATH="/opt/conda/envs/borzoi-gpu/bin:$PATH"
    exec python3 /src/script_and_utils/borzoi_predictor_API.py "$@"
%startscript
    echo "Container is starting with Borzoi GPU environment activated"
    export PATH="/opt/conda/envs/borzoi-gpu/bin:$PATH"
    exec python3 /src/script_and_utils/borzoi_predictor_API.py "$@"
%labels
    Author "Satyam Priyadarshi"
    Version "1.0"
    Description "A RESTful Borzoi Predictor for the Genomic API for Model Evaluation Framework"

%help
    This container for Predictor includes:
    - Flask-based REST API for sequence processing and prediction handling.
    - Integrated Borzoi model with its dependencies and `borzoi-gpu` conda environment created using `borzoi_gpu_environment.yml`.
    - Baskerville and Borzoi packages, installed from local source copies of repositories (as of March 2025), which also contain 
      helper scripts and 4 replicate model weights (pre-downloaded). 
    - Support scripts like `error_checking_functions.py`, `schema_validation.py`, `predictor_content_handler.py`, 
      and `predictor_help_message.json`.
    
    NOTE: This container requires a GPU for execution because the Borzoi model relies on GPU-accelerated operations from TensorFlow. 
    Running on CPU may lead to excessive memory usage and thread allocation failures.

    Usage:
    We encourage using the pre-built container for this model that are hosted on Zenodo. Visit https://github.com/de-Boer-Lab/Genomic-API-for-Model-Evaluation for more information.

    However, if you are building the container using the provided definition file, ensure you have the following directory structure on the host:

    ```bash
    path/to/src
    ├── README.md
    ├── borzoi_API_script_and_utils
    │   ├── baskerville/
    │   ├── borzoi/
    │   │   ├── LICENSE
    │   │   ├── README.md
    │   │   ├── borzoi_logo.png
    │   │   ├── data/
    │   │   ├── examples/
    │   │   │   └── saved_models/
    │   │   │       ├── f3c0/train/model0_best.h5
    │   │   │       ├── f3c1/train/model0_best.h5
    │   │   │       ├── f3c2/train/model0_best.h5
    │   │   │       └── f3c3/train/model0_best.h5
    │   │   ├── pyproject.toml
    │   │   ├── src/
    │   │   └── tutorials/
    │   ├── borzoi_predict_codebase.py
    │   ├── borzoi_utils.py
    │   ├── model_validation.py
    │   └── simplify_targets/
    │       ├── borzoi_human_targets_simplified.txt
    │       └── parse_borzoi_target.py
    ├── borzoi_gpu_environment.yml
    ├── predictor.def
    ├── borzoi_human_predictor.sif
    └── script_and_utils/
        ├── borzoi_predictor_API.py
        ├── error_checking_functions.py
        ├── schema_validation.py
        ├── predictor_content_handler.py
        └── predictor_help_message.json
    ```

    Model Availability:
    The model weights (.h5 files) should be pre-downloaded and placed in the `borzoi/examples/saved_models/` directory 
    before building the container. If you need to download them, run the `download_models.sh` script from the 
    `borzoi_API_script_and_utils/borzoi/` directory:

    ```bash
    cd borzoi
    ./download_models.sh
    ```

    **NOTE:** Downloading the model weights requires python modules like `pyfaidx`. For more details regarding the models, 
    please refer to [Borzoi Github Repository](https://github.com/calico/borzoi?tab=readme-ov-file#model-availability).

    The saved models should be arranged as follows (based on HUMAN training data only):

    ```bash
    borzoi_API_script_and_utils/borzoi/examples/saved_models/
    ├── f3c0/train/model0_best.h5
    ├── f3c1/train/model0_best.h5
    ├── f3c2/train/model0_best.h5
    └── f3c3/train/model0_best.h5
    ```
    
    Build the container (SIF):
    ```bash
    apptainer build borzoi_human_predictor.sif predictor.def
    ```

    Testing the Container:
    
    Once running, test the API endpoints:
    ```bash
    # Check supported formats
    curl http://172.xx.xx.xx:5000/formats

    # Get help information
    curl http://172.xx.xx.xx:5000/help
    ```
    
    Run the container:
    ```bash
    apptainer run --nv --containall borzoi_human_predictor.sif HOST_IP HOST_PORT MATCHER_IP MATCHER_PORT
    ```

    Details:
    - The container runs a Flask REST API that receives prediction requests via HTTP endpoints.
    - Replace `HOST_IP` and `HOST_PORT` with the IP address and port where the Predictor API should listen.
    - Replace `MATCHER_IP` and `MATCHER_PORT` with the IP and port configuration of the Matcher service for cell type 
      and track name resolution. If Matcher is not needed for your task, provide placeholder values.
    - The `--nv` flag enables NVIDIA GPU and CUDA library support for running GPU-accelerated applications.
    - The `--containall` flag ensures a clean, isolated environment for reproducible runs.

    API Endpoints:
    - GET  /formats - Returns supported request and response formats
    - GET  /help    - Returns predictor metadata and usage information
    - POST /predict - Main endpoint for submitting prediction requests

    Purpose:
    - Facilitates genomic model evaluation and prediction using the Borzoi model.
    - Designed to integrate seamlessly with the Genomic API for Model Evaluation (GAME) framework.
    - Supports communication with Matcher service for flexible cell type and track name resolution.

    Example Command:
    ```bash
    apptainer run --nv --containall borzoi_human_predictor.sif 172.xx.xx.xx 5000 192.xx.xx.xx 6000
    ```

    Arguments:
    1. `HOST_IP`: IP address where the Predictor API will listen (e.g. 0.0.0.0 for all interfaces).
    2. `HOST_PORT`: Port number the Predictor API will listen on (e.g. 5000).
    3. `MATCHER_IP`: IP address of the Matcher service (Optional).
    4. `MATCHER_PORT`: Port number of the Matcher service (Optional).